utchinson Publishing.   {{ISBN|0-09-169231-8}}\n*Lester G (1985). ''Berries to Bulldogs.'' Lester - Townsend Publishing. {{ISBN|0-949853-06-2}}\n*NRL Official Information Handbook (2001\u20132007). ''Season Guide.''\n*Middleton D (1987\u20132006). ''The Official NSWRL, ARL, NRL Yearbook / Annual.''\n*Christensen EE (1946\u20131977). ''NSWRL Yearbook.''\n*''Rugby League Review (2003\u20132007).''\n*''Big League (1974\u20132007).''\n*''Rugby League Week (1970\u20132007).''\n*''The Rugby League News.''\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.bulldogs.com.au/ Official Bulldogs Website]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070422230115/http://www.bulldogs.com.au/teamstore/ Official Bulldogs Team Store]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070314152556/http://www.stats.rleague.com/rl/teams/canterbury/canterbury_idx.html Bulldogs Statistics]\n*[http://www.backtobelmore.com.au/ Back to Belmore - The Official Campaign Website]\n\n{{Bulldogs Rugby League Football Club}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:History of the Canterbury-Bankstown Bulldogs}}\n[[Category:Canterbury-Bankstown Bulldogs]]\n[[Category:History of rugby league|Bulldogs Rugby League Football Club]]\n[[Category:History of sport in Australia by team|Canterbury-Bankstown Bulldogs]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 19-6 \u2192 19\u20136 (21), 24-14 \u2192 24\u201314 (13)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_the_Canterbury-Bankstown_Bulldogs"}
{"title_page": "Pawnbrokers in Hong Kong", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Use Hong Kong English|date=May 2014}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Underlinked|date=January 2014}}\n{{copyedit|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n[[File:NamCheongPawnshop.jpg|thumb|upright|Nam Cheong Pawnshop in [[Sham Shui Po]].]]\n\nIn 2014, there were 200 '''[[pawnbroker]]s in Hong Kong''', with the number increasing slightly over the next several years.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://passhonpropawnshop.wordpress.com/2017/04/29/%E7%9E%AC%E9%96%93%E7%9C%8B%E7%95%B6%E9%8B%AA/|title=\u7576\u92ea-\u751f\u5b58\u4e4b\u79d8 |last1=ANNA |first1=YIU|date=29 April 2017 |website= passhonpropawnshop|publisher= |access-date= 4 March 2019|quote=}}</ref> [[Pawnbroking|Pawn shops]] are one of the oldest businesses in [[Hong Kong]]{{Citation needed|reason=This isn't really backed up by anything else in this article|date=January 2018}}.\n{{TOC limit|2}}\n\n== History and Development ==\nThere have been pawnbrokers in Hong Kong for over 200 years. According to Guangdong Annals, there were 16 pawnbrokers in Hong Kong in 1821. The oldest pawnbrokers in Hong Kong being Jeun Yun Aat ({{lang-za|\u6649\u6e90\u62bc}}) .<ref>https://hk.history.museum/documents/54401/54616/Sen_02_full.pdf</ref>\nIn 1837, the [[Yuen Long]] bazaar let the third, sixth, ninth day of each month of the lunar calendar be a market day. Expatriate Chinese and locals, always \u201cRuins\u201d({{lang-za|\u8d81\u589f}}) in the morning. Customers make more transactions because there are more discounts on that day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/savehkheritages/posts/574831689530488|title=\u5168\u6c11\u4fdd\u80b2\u884c\u52d5|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2019-03-11}}</ref>\nIn 1926, the [[Hong Kong government]] strengthened its regulations on pawn shops and promulgated pawn legislation. Since then, pawnbrokers are required to be licensed establishments.<ref>The Hong Kong & Kowloon Pawnbrokers\u2019 Association Limited. http://www.pawn.com.hk/?mod=site_pawn_assoc_history . Extracted on 04 November 2013</ref> These regulations allowed the industry to become more popular{{Citation needed|reason=Reliable source needed for the whole sentence|date=January 2018}}.\n\nThe activities of the pawnbrokers were limited by the Japanese during the [[Japanese occupation of Hong Kong]] in the [[Second World War]]. In 1943, Japan required Hong Kong to use [[Japanese military yen]] to exchange inter-medium. In 1945, the Japanese announced surrender in the Second World War, and the [[Japanese military yen]] became useless paper. Most people go to a pawnbroker and have some Hong Kong Dollars for their daily life. To circulate funds and jump-start the economy, the Hong Kong Government urged the pawn industry to revive itself. With government support, The Hong Kong & Kowloon Pawnbrokers' Association Limited was set up in 1947. There were only 11 members at the time. Between 1950 and 1960, the number of members increased to more than 90, reaching 138 in 1994. Today the Association has more than 161 members and combined with non-member pawn shops, there are approximately 250 pawn shops in Hong Kong. Pawn shops are mainly located on [[Hong Kong Island]], particularly [[Central, Hong Kong|Central]] and [[Kowloon]]. Because many jewelers and goldsmiths shop are located in Central, the mortgage and loan amount is usually higher.<ref>\u65bc\u5f65\u5317. \u9999\u6e2f\u7576\u92ea\u4f55\u4ee5\u7d93\u4e45\u4e0d\u8870\uff1a\"\u62bc\"\u5b57\u62db\u724c\u540e\u6709\u4e7e\u5764 {{cite web |url=http://hm.people.com.cn/BIG5/42280/42458/42580/3134007.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-11-11 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116213249/http://hm.people.com.cn/BIG5/42280/42458/42580/3134007.html |archivedate=16 January 2014 |df=dmy-all }} Extracted on 3/4 November 2013</ref>{{Citation needed|reason=for entire paragraph|date=January 2018}}\n\nIn order to prevent the sale of stolen property in pawn shops, Hong Kong law stipulates that pawn shops must check the IDs of would-be clients looking to pawn items, which are under strict verification and registration. Pawn shops must keep digital records of all exchanges, and if any suspicious items are found in the pawn shop, they must immediately notify the police.{{Citation needed|reason=for entire paragraph|date=January 2018}}\n\nOn 12 March 2013, the first \"Pawn Shop Stocks\", Oi Wah Pawnshop Credit Holdings Limited (01319.HK), was listed on the [[Hong Kong Stock Exchange]]. This novel sort of pawn shop can cooperate with the market instead of going with the set square to constitute a special private credit market in Hong Kong.<ref>Oi Wah Pawnshop Credit Limited. http://www.pawnshop.com.hk/?mod=site_oi_wah_tch_about_us Extracted on 04 November 2013</ref>{{Relevance inline|paragraph|date=January 2018}}\n\n== Features of pawn shops ==\n[[File:Pawnshop front.jpg|thumb|upright|Dong Zung]]\n\n=== Design ===\n==== Dong Zung ====\nA dong zung is a large rectangular wooden screen, similar to a pair of doors, located right behind the entrance of the pawn shop. The screen is tall enough to block passersby from seeing inside. Clients can be concealed by the board to avoid embarrassment.\n\n==== Pawning counter ====\nThe counter of the pawn shop, which is behind the tall board, is typically higher than the average person. There are window frames in the counter. Clients need to give their mortgaged properties upward to the pawning counter. This design shows the higher status of the pawnbrokers. Prices seem to be lower due to the psychological effect caused by this design{{Citation needed|reason=Need a source for psychological effect|date=January 2018}}. Another reason for setting a high counter is for security. It is hard for passersby and clients to see the environment and workers inside the pawn shop.\n\n=== Names of pawn shops ===\nPawn shops are a traditional industry in China. The majority of the shops use names including words meaning harmonious (for example 'tung' (\u540c), 'wo' (\u548c)) and/or prosperous (for example 'chang' (\u660c), 'fat' (\u767c), 'fung' (\u8c50)). The idea behind such a name is an entreaty and hope for having glorious and flourishing business development.<ref>\u5468\u6709\u6cc9. \u9999\u6e2f\u4eba\u7684\u2018\u4e8c\u53d4\u516c\u2019- \u6dfa\u8ac7\u7576\u92ea http://www.somanhing.com/ftihk/pdf/assignment/pawnshop.pdf Extracted on 3 November 2013</ref> {{Unreliable source?|date=December 2017}}\n\n== Pawning procedure ==\n[[File:ZeCauBaan.jpg|thumb|upright|Ze Cau Baan]]\n# The customer visits the pawn shop and gives the item to be pawned to the shop assistant.\n# The shop assistant will check the serial numbers and model of the item to identify whether it is on a list that have been reported as missing or stolen by the local law enforcement.<ref>{{cite book |title=\u871a\u8a9e (\u7b2c\u5341\u4e09\u671f) |date=2015 |publisher=\u5dba\u5357\u6587\u793e |pages=10\u201312 |url=https://commons.ln.edu.hk/lusu_literaturesociety_magazine/13/ |accessdate=4 March 2019}}</ref>\n# If it is not a stolen or missing item, the shop assistant will assay the item based on the original price and the current condition of the product.\n# If the customer accepts the valuation, the shop assistant will verify the documents that can prove the identity of the customers as the pawnbroker shall not receive in pawn any goods from the person who is under the age of 17 years.<ref>{{cite journal |title=\u3010\u884c\u5167\u4eba\u89e3\u79d8\u3011\u7576\u8216\u9760\u4e5c\u5622\u8cfa\u9322\uff1f \u4e8c\u53d4\u516c\u4e00\u7747\u5c31\u77e5\u908a\u4ef6\u4fc2\u5931\u7269 |journal=Apple Daily \u860b\u679c\u65e5\u5831 |issue=2018/09/04 |url=https://hk.lifestyle.appledaily.com/lifestyle/realtime/article/20180904/58640478 |accessdate=4 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Cap. 166 PAWNBROKERS ORDINANCE \u2500 Section 21 Prohibition on pawnbrokers when receiving goods in pawn |url=https://www.elegislation.gov.hk/hk/cap166!en@1997-07-01T00:00:00?SEARCH_WITHIN_CAP_TXT=PAWNBROKERS%20ORDINANCE |website=www.elegislation.gov.hk |publisher=Hong Kong e-Legislation |accessdate=4 March 2019}}</ref>\n# The pawn ticket and cash will be issued to the customers.\n# The customers will count the cash immediately and the process is completed if there is no further problem.<ref>[http://www.pawn.com.hk/?mod=site_pawn_assoc_procedure The Hong Kong & Kowloon Pawnbrokers\u2019 Association Limited]. Extracted on 3 November 2013</ref>\n\n== Special terms in pawning ==\n* Ceot Zat ({{lang-za|\u51fa\u8cea}}): Clients offering up items to be pawned.\n* Ji Suk Gung/Ciu Fung ({{lang-za|\u4e8c\u53d4\u516c/\u671d\u5949}}): A worker who identifies and appraises the pawned goods.\n* Maa Zi ({{lang-za|\u78bc\u5b50}}): The number sheet used to track exchanges.\n* Zaap Gaa ({{lang-za|\u96dc\u67b6}}): Clocks, antiques, etc.\n* Jyut Lik ({{lang-za|\u6708\u66c6}}): The lunar calendar. Since months for the lunar calendar are one to two days shorter than the solar calendar, if pawnee repays the loan one day later than the deadline, they need to pay interests for one additional month.\n* Lau Dong Ban ({{lang-za|\u6d41\u7576\u54c1}): The deadline for repaying loans and getting back the pawned item(s) ends.\n* Leoi Gung Gwang ({{lang-za|\u96f7\u516c\u8f5f}}): The mortgage interest is as terrible as the rumblings of thunder.\n* Ze Cau Baan ({{lang-za|\u906e\u7f9e\u677f}}): A big shield standing in front of the main gate. It is used to hide the situation inside the store.\n* Gau Ceot Sap Saam Gwai ({{lang-za|\u4e5d\u51fa\u5341\u4e09\u6b78}}): The method pawn shops uses to calculate interest. For instance, when the pawn is worth about 10 dollars, only nine dollars will be lent and in the end thirteen dollars will be needed to repay to loan.<ref>[http://www.macaupawnbrokers.com/list.asp?id=328 Macau General Chamber of Pawnbrokers] Extracted on 3 November 2013</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Pawnbrokers in Hong Kong}}\n* [https://zolimacitymag.com/behind-the-screen-doors-of-hong-kongs-pawn-shops-centuries-of-tradition/ Doors of Hong Kong's Pawn Shops, Centuries of Tradition]\n\n[[Category:Retailing in Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Pawn shops]]\n[[Category:Retail financial services]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Use Hong Kong English|date=May 2014}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Underlinked|date=January 2014}}\n{{copyedit|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n[[File:NamCheongPawnshop.jpg|thumb|upright|Nam Cheong Pawnshop in [[Sham Shui Po]].]]\n\nIn 2014, there were 200 '''[[pawnbroker]]s in Hong Kong''', with the number increasing slightly over the next several years, remaining unchanged until 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://passhonpropawnshop.wordpress.com/2017/04/29/%E7%9E%AC%E9%96%93%E7%9C%8B%E7%95%B6%E9%8B%AA/|title=\u7576\u92ea-\u751f\u5b58\u4e4b\u79d8 |last1=ANNA |first1=YIU|date=29 April 2017 |website= passhonpropawnshop|publisher= |access-date= 4 March 2019|quote=}}</ref> [[Pawnbroking|Pawn shops]] are one of the oldest businesses in [[Hong Kong]]{{Citation needed|reason=This isn't really backed up by anything else in this article|date=January 2018}}.\n{{TOC limit|2}}\n\n== History and Development ==\nThere have been pawnbrokers in Hong Kong for over 200 years. According to Guangdong Annals, there were 16 pawnbrokers in Hong Kong in 1821. The oldest pawnbrokers in Hong Kong being Jeun Yun Aat ({{lang-za|\u6649\u6e90\u62bc}}) .<ref>https://hk.history.museum/documents/54401/54616/Sen_02_full.pdf</ref>\nIn 1837, the [[Yuen Long]] bazaar let the third, sixth, ninth day of each month of the lunar calendar be a market day. Expatriate Chinese and locals, always \u201cRuins\u201d({{lang-za|\u8d81\u589f}}) in the morning. Customers make more transactions because there are more discounts on that day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/savehkheritages/posts/574831689530488|title=\u5168\u6c11\u4fdd\u80b2\u884c\u52d5|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2019-03-11}}</ref>\nIn 1926, the [[Hong Kong government]] strengthened its regulations on pawn shops and promulgated pawn legislation. Since then, pawnbrokers are required to be licensed establishments.<ref>The Hong Kong & Kowloon Pawnbrokers\u2019 Association Limited. http://www.pawn.com.hk/?mod=site_pawn_assoc_history . Extracted on 04 November 2013</ref> These regulations allowed the industry to become more popular{{Citation needed|reason=Reliable source needed for the whole sentence|date=January 2018}}.\n\nThe activities of the pawnbrokers were limited by the Japanese during the [[Japanese occupation of Hong Kong]] in the [[Second World War]]. In 1943, Japan required Hong Kong to use [[Japanese military yen]] to exchange inter-medium. In 1945, the Japanese announced surrender in the Second World War, and the [[Japanese military yen]] became useless paper. Most people go to a pawnbroker and have some Hong Kong Dollars for their daily life. To circulate funds and jump-start the economy, the Hong Kong Government urged the pawn industry to revive itself. With government support, The Hong Kong & Kowloon Pawnbrokers' Association Limited was set up in 1947. There were only 11 members at the time. Between 1950 and 1960, the number of members increased to more than 90, reaching 138 in 1994. Today the Association has more than 161 members and combined with non-member pawn shops, there are approximately 250 pawn shops in Hong Kong. Pawn shops are mainly located on [[Hong Kong Island]], particularly [[Central, Hong Kong|Central]] and [[Kowloon]]. Because many jewelers and goldsmiths shop are located in Central, the mortgage and loan amount is usually higher.<ref>\u65bc\u5f65\u5317. \u9999\u6e2f\u7576\u92ea\u4f55\u4ee5\u7d93\u4e45\u4e0d\u8870\uff1a\"\u62bc\"\u5b57\u62db\u724c\u540e\u6709\u4e7e\u5764 {{cite web |url=http://hm.people.com.cn/BIG5/42280/42458/42580/3134007.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-11-11 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116213249/http://hm.people.com.cn/BIG5/42280/42458/42580/3134007.html |archivedate=16 January 2014 |df=dmy-all }} Extracted on 3/4 November 2013</ref>{{Citation needed|reason=for entire paragraph|date=January 2018}}\n\nIn order to prevent the sale of stolen property in pawn shops, Hong Kong law stipulates that pawn shops must check the IDs of would-be clients looking to pawn items, which are under strict verification and registration. Pawn shops must keep digital records of all exchanges, and if any suspicious items are found in the pawn shop, they must immediately notify the police.{{Citation needed|reason=for entire paragraph|date=January 2018}}\n\nOn 12 March 2013, the first \"Pawn Shop Stocks\", Oi Wah Pawnshop Credit Holdings Limited (01319.HK), was listed on the [[Hong Kong Stock Exchange]]. This novel sort of pawn shop can cooperate with the market instead of going with the set square to constitute a special private credit market in Hong Kong.<ref>Oi Wah Pawnshop Credit Limited. http://www.pawnshop.com.hk/?mod=site_oi_wah_tch_about_us Extracted on 04 November 2013</ref>{{Relevance inline|paragraph|date=January 2018}}\n\n== Features of pawn shops ==\n[[File:Pawnshop front.jpg|thumb|upright|Dong Zung]]\n\n=== Design ===\n==== Dong Zung ====\nA dong zung is a large rectangular wooden screen, similar to a pair of doors, located right behind the entrance of the pawn shop. The screen is tall enough to block passersby from seeing inside. Clients can be concealed by the board to avoid embarrassment.\n\n==== Pawning counter ====\nThe counter of the pawn shop, which is behind the tall board, is typically higher than the average person. There are window frames in the counter. Clients need to give their mortgaged properties upward to the pawning counter. This design shows the higher status of the pawnbrokers. Prices seem to be lower due to the psychological effect caused by this design{{Citation needed|reason=Need a source for psychological effect|date=January 2018}}. Another reason for setting a high counter is for security. It is hard for passersby and clients to see the environment and workers inside the pawn shop.\n\n=== Names of pawn shops ===\nPawn shops are a traditional industry in China. The majority of the shops use names including words meaning harmonious (for example 'tung' (\u540c), 'wo' (\u548c)) and/or prosperous (for example 'chang' (\u660c), 'fat' (\u767c), 'fung' (\u8c50)). The idea behind such a name is an entreaty and hope for having glorious and flourishing business development.<ref>\u5468\u6709\u6cc9. \u9999\u6e2f\u4eba\u7684\u2018\u4e8c\u53d4\u516c\u2019- \u6dfa\u8ac7\u7576\u92ea http://www.somanhing.com/ftihk/pdf/assignment/pawnshop.pdf Extracted on 3 November 2013</ref> {{Unreliable source?|date=December 2017}}\n\n== Pawning procedure ==\n[[File:ZeCauBaan.jpg|thumb|upright|Ze Cau Baan]]\n# The customer visits the pawn shop and gives the item to be pawned to the shop assistant.\n# The shop assistant will check the serial numbers and model of the item to identify whether it is on a list that have been reported as missing or stolen by the local law enforcement.<ref>{{cite book |title=\u871a\u8a9e (\u7b2c\u5341\u4e09\u671f) |date=2015 |publisher=\u5dba\u5357\u6587\u793e |pages=10\u201312 |url=https://commons.ln.edu.hk/lusu_literaturesociety_magazine/13/ |accessdate=4 March 2019}}</ref>\n# If it is not a stolen or missing item, the shop assistant will assay the item based on the original price and the current condition of the product.\n# If the customer accepts the valuation, the shop assistant will verify the documents that can prove the identity of the customers as the pawnbroker shall not receive in pawn any goods from the person who is under the age of 17 years.<ref>{{cite journal |title=\u3010\u884c\u5167\u4eba\u89e3\u79d8\u3011\u7576\u8216\u9760\u4e5c\u5622\u8cfa\u9322\uff1f \u4e8c\u53d4\u516c\u4e00\u7747\u5c31\u77e5\u908a\u4ef6\u4fc2\u5931\u7269 |journal=Apple Daily \u860b\u679c\u65e5\u5831 |issue=2018/09/04 |url=https://hk.lifestyle.appledaily.com/lifestyle/realtime/article/20180904/58640478 |accessdate=4 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Cap. 166 PAWNBROKERS ORDINANCE \u2500 Section 21 Prohibition on pawnbrokers when receiving goods in pawn |url=https://www.elegislation.gov.hk/hk/cap166!en@1997-07-01T00:00:00?SEARCH_WITHIN_CAP_TXT=PAWNBROKERS%20ORDINANCE |website=www.elegislation.gov.hk |publisher=Hong Kong e-Legislation |accessdate=4 March 2019}}</ref>\n# The pawn ticket and cash will be issued to the customers.\n# The customers will count the cash immediately and the process is completed if there is no further problem.<ref>[http://www.pawn.com.hk/?mod=site_pawn_assoc_procedure The Hong Kong & Kowloon Pawnbrokers\u2019 Association Limited]. Extracted on 3 November 2013</ref>\n\n== Special terms in pawning ==\n* Ceot Zat ({{lang-za|\u51fa\u8cea}}): Clients offering up items to be pawned.\n* Ji Suk Gung/Ciu Fung ({{lang-za|\u4e8c\u53d4\u516c/\u671d\u5949}}): A worker who identifies and appraises the pawned goods.\n* Maa Zi ({{lang-za|\u78bc\u5b50}}): The number sheet used to track exchanges.\n* Zaap Gaa ({{lang-za|\u96dc\u67b6}}): Clocks, antiques, etc.\n* Jyut Lik ({{lang-za|\u6708\u66c6}}): The lunar calendar. Since months for the lunar calendar are one to two days shorter than the solar calendar, if pawnee repays the loan one day later than the deadline, they need to pay interests for one additional month.\n* Lau Dong Ban ({{lang-za|\u6d41\u7576\u54c1}): The deadline for repaying loans and getting back the pawned item(s) ends.\n* Leoi Gung Gwang ({{lang-za|\u96f7\u516c\u8f5f}}): The mortgage interest is as terrible as the rumblings of thunder.\n* Ze Cau Baan ({{lang-za|\u906e\u7f9e\u677f}}): A big shield standing in front of the main gate. It is used to hide the situation inside the store.\n* Gau Ceot Sap Saam Gwai ({{lang-za|\u4e5d\u51fa\u5341\u4e09\u6b78}}): The method pawn shops uses to calculate interest. For instance, when the pawn is worth about 10 dollars, only nine dollars will be lent and in the end thirteen dollars will be needed to repay to loan.<ref>[http://www.macaupawnbrokers.com/list.asp?id=328 Macau General Chamber of Pawnbrokers] Extracted on 3 November 2013</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Pawnbrokers in Hong Kong}}\n* [https://zolimacitymag.com/behind-the-screen-doors-of-hong-kongs-pawn-shops-centuries-of-tradition/ Doors of Hong Kong's Pawn Shops, Centuries of Tradition]\n\n[[Category:Retailing in Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Pawn shops]]\n[[Category:Retail financial services]]\n", "name_user": "MichaelMichael10000", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing an illogical sentence", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pawnbrokers_in_Hong_Kong"}
{"title_page": "Mark Stevens (art critic)", "text_new": "'''Mark Stevens''' (born August 14, 1951) is an American writer who was co-awarded the 2005 [[Pulitzer Prize for Biography or Autobiography]] with [[Annalyn Swan]] for ''De Kooning: An American Master''. During his writing career, Stevens was an art critic for ''[[Newsweek]]'', ''[[The New Republic]]'' and ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]'' between the 1970s to 2000s. Other publications by Stevens include a 1981 work [[Richard Diebenkorn]]'s art and a 1984 book called ''Summer of the City''.\n\n==Early life and education==\nOn August 14, 1951, Stevens was born in [[New York City]]. For his post-secondary education, Stevens received a [[Bachelor of Arts]] from [[Princeton University]] in 1973 and a [[Master of Arts]] from [[King's College, Cambridge|King's College]] in 1975.<ref name=contemporaryauthors>{{cite encyclopedia |editor1-last=May |editor-first1=Hal |editor2-last=Trosky |editor2-first=Susan M. |encyclopedia=Contemporary Authors |title=Stevens, Mark 1951\u2014 |url=https://archive.org/details/contemporaryauth122halm/page/430 |access-date=17 February 2020 |year=1988 |publisher=Gale Research Company |volume=122 |location=Detroit |isbn=0810319225 |page=431}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nStevens began his writing career as a freelancer in 1975 before becoming an art critic for ''[[Newsweek]]'' in 1977.<ref name=contemporaryauthors/> He remained at Newsweek until August 1988 while expanding his writings with ''[[The New Republic]]'' and ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]''.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=A Hite Report, A Newsweek Newcomer |magazine=New York |date=February 6, 1989 |volume=22 |issue=6 |page=12 |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=qugCAAAAMBAJ |accessdate=18 February 2020}}</ref> At ''The New Republic'', Stevens started critiquing art in 1986 before continuing his art critic career with ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]'' in 1996.<ref>{{cite news |title=Critic, author talks of fame, political art on campus |url=https://missoulian.com/entertainment/arts-and-theatre/article_f072a1cc-61ef-11e0-aa39-001cc4c03286.html |accessdate=28 September 2019 |work=Missoulian |date=8 April 2011}}</ref> Stevens remained with the magazine until his resignation in 2007.<ref>{{cite news |title=Critic Jerry Saltz Heads to New York mag |url=https://observer.com/2007/03/critic-jerry-saltz-heads-to-emnew-yorkem/ |accessdate=28 September 2019 |work=New York Observer |date=30 March 2007}}</ref>\n\nOutside of art, Stevens published a work about [[Richard Diebenkorn]]'s artworks in 1981. In 1984, he released his first book ''Summer of the City'' in 1984 while writing for Newsweek.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |editor-last=Hall |editor-first=Sharon |encyclopedia=Contemporary literary criticism |title=Mark Stevens 19?- |url=https://archive.org/details/contemporarylite34gale/page/110 |access-date=1 October 2019 |year=1985 |publisher=Gale Research Company |volume=34 |location=Detroit |isbn=0810344084 |issn=0091-3421 |page=111}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Burns |first1=Ann |last2=Waite |first2=Deborah |title=First Novelists |journal=Library Journal |date=15 March 1984 |volume=109 |issue=5 |page=554 |url=https://archive.org/details/libraryjournal109jan/page/554 |accessdate=2 October 2019}}</ref> In 1989, Stevens and his wife [[Annalyn Swan]] signed with ''[[Bantam Books]]'' for a future biography about [[Willem de Kooning]].<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Media Notes From All Over |magazine=New York |date=December 18, 1989 |volume=22 |issue=50 |page=10 |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=NugCAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA10 |accessdate=18 February 2020}}</ref> After spending ten years on the writing process, ''de Kooning: An American Master'' was released in 2004 by ''[[Alfred A. Knopf]]''.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bonetti |first1=David |title=de Kooning biographers discuss their prize-winning project |work=St. Louis Post-Dispatch |date=October 23, 2005 |page=F11}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Fischer |first1=Jack |title=A master gets his due |work=Wisconsin State Journal |date=December 12, 2004 |page=G3}}</ref> In 2008, Stevens and Swan reached a deal with Knopf for a future [[Francis Bacon]] biography.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Eyman |first1=Scott |title=In the pipeline... |work=The Marshall News Messenger |date=12 October 2008 |page=6B}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\nStevens won the 2005 [[Pulitzer Prize for Biography or Autobiography]] alongside his wife [[Annalyn Swan]] for ''De Kooning: An American Master''.<ref>{{cite news |title=Pulitizer winner sketches |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/04/05/nyregion/pulitzer-winner-sketches.html |accessdate=28 September 2019 |work=The New York Times |date=5 April 2005}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{PulitzerPrize BiographyorAutobiographyAuthors 2001\u20132025}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:American writers]]\n[[Category:American art critics]]\n[[Category:Newsweek people]]\n[[Category:The New Republic people]]\n[[Category:Vanity Fair (magazine) people]]\n[[Category:Pulitzer Prize for Biography or Autobiography winners]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "'''Mark Stevens''' (born August 14, 1951) is an American writer who was co-awarded the 2005 [[Pulitzer Prize for Biography or Autobiography]] with [[Annalyn Swan]] for ''De Kooning: An American Master''. During his writing career, Stevens was an art critic for ''[[Newsweek]]'', ''[[The New Republic]]'' and ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]'' between the 1970s to 2000s. Other publications by Stevens include a 1981 work [[Richard Diebenkorn]]'s art and a 1984 book called ''Summer of the City''. \n\n==Early life and education==\nOn August 14, 1951, Stevens was born in [[New York City]]. For his post-secondary education, Stevens received a [[Bachelor of Arts]] from [[Princeton University]] in 1973 and a [[Master of Arts]] from [[King's College, Cambridge|King's College]] in 1975.<ref name=contemporaryauthors>{{cite encyclopedia |editor1-last=May |editor-first1=Hal |editor2-last=Trosky |editor2-first=Susan M. |encyclopedia=Contemporary Authors |title=Stevens, Mark 1951\u2014 |url=https://archive.org/details/contemporaryauth122halm/page/430 |access-date=17 February 2020 |year=1988 |publisher=Gale Research Company |volume=122 |location=Detroit |isbn=0810319225 |page=431}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nStevens began his writing career as a freelancer in 1975 before becoming an art critic for ''[[Newsweek]]'' in 1977.<ref name=contemporaryauthors/> He remained at Newsweek until August 1988 while expanding his writings with ''[[The New Republic]]'' and ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]''.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=A Hite Report, A Newsweek Newcomer |magazine=New York |date=February 6, 1989 |volume=22 |issue=6 |page=12 |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=qugCAAAAMBAJ |accessdate=18 February 2020}}</ref> At ''The New Republic'', Stevens started critiquing art in 1986 before continuing his art critic career with ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]'' in 1996.<ref>{{cite news |title=Critic, author talks of fame, political art on campus |url=https://missoulian.com/entertainment/arts-and-theatre/article_f072a1cc-61ef-11e0-aa39-001cc4c03286.html |accessdate=28 September 2019 |work=Missoulian |date=8 April 2011}}</ref> Stevens remained with the magazine until his resignation in 2007.<ref>{{cite news |title=Critic Jerry Saltz Heads to New York mag |url=https://observer.com/2007/03/critic-jerry-saltz-heads-to-emnew-yorkem/ |accessdate=28 September 2019 |work=New York Observer |date=30 March 2007}}</ref>\n\nOutside of art, Stevens published a work about [[Richard Diebenkorn]]'s artworks in 1981. In 1984, he released his first book ''Summer of the City'' in 1984 while writing for Newsweek.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |editor-last=Hall |editor-first=Sharon |encyclopedia=Contemporary literary criticism |title=Mark Stevens 19?- |url=https://archive.org/details/contemporarylite34gale/page/110 |access-date=1 October 2019 |year=1985 |publisher=Gale Research Company |volume=34 |location=Detroit |isbn=0810344084 |issn=0091-3421 |page=111}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Burns |first1=Ann |last2=Waite |first2=Deborah |title=First Novelists |journal=Library Journal |date=15 March 1984 |volume=109 |issue=5 |page=554 |url=https://archive.org/details/libraryjournal109jan/page/554 |accessdate=2 October 2019}}</ref> In 1989, Stevens and his wife [[Annalyn Swan]] signed with ''[[Bantam Books]]'' for a future biography about [[Willem de Kooning]].<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Media Notes From All Over |magazine=New York |date=December 18, 1989 |volume=22 |issue=50 |page=10 |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=NugCAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA10 |accessdate=18 February 2020}}</ref> After spending ten years on the writing process, ''de Kooning: An American Master'' was released in 2004 by ''[[Alfred A. Knopf]]''.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bonetti |first1=David |title=de Kooning biographers discuss their prize-winning project |work=St. Louis Post-Dispatch |date=October 23, 2005 |page=F11}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Fischer |first1=Jack |title=A master gets his due |work=Wisconsin State Journal |date=December 12, 2004 |page=G3}}</ref> In 2008, Stevens and Swan reached a deal with Knopf for a future [[Francis Bacon]] biography.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Eyman |first1=Scott |title=In the pipeline... |work=The Marshall News Messenger |date=12 October 2008 |page=6B}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\nStevens won the 2005 [[Pulitzer Prize for Biography or Autobiography]] alongside his wife [[Annalyn Swan]] for ''De Kooning: An American Master''.<ref>{{cite news |title=Pulitizer winner sketches |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/04/05/nyregion/pulitzer-winner-sketches.html |accessdate=28 September 2019 |work=The New York Times |date=5 April 2005}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{PulitzerPrize BiographyorAutobiographyAuthors 2001\u20132025}}\n\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:American writers]]\n[[Category:American art critics]]\n[[Category:Newsweek people]]\n[[Category:The New Republic people]]\n[[Category:Vanity Fair (magazine) people]]\n[[Category:Pulitzer Prize for Biography or Autobiography winners]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mark_Stevens_(art_critic)"}
{"title_page": "2016 Men's World Floorball Championships qualifying", "text_new": "{{use dmy dates|date=January 2016}}\nThe '''qualifying''' for the '''[[2016 Men's World Floorball Championships]]''' took place between 2 and 14 February 2016. A total of 33 teams<ref name=\"General schedule\">{{cite web\n | url = http://www.floorball.org/news.asp?alue=775&id_tiedote=4602\n | title = Men\u00b4s WFC 2016 Qualification match schedules \u2013 16.10.2015\n | date = 16 October 2015\n | website = www.floorball.org\n | publisher = [[International Floorball Federation]]\n | access-date = 12 January 2016}}</ref> competed for fifteen spots. The final tournament was organized by [[Latvia]] in December 2016.\n\n==Overview==\nNumbers in brackets show the ranking before the qualification started, which is based on results from the last two World Championships.<ref name=\"General schedule\" />\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:100%;\"\n|-\n!width=17%| Europe 1\n!width=17%| Europe 2\n!width=17%| Europe 3\n!width=17%| Europe 4\n!width=17%| Asia/Oceania\n!width=17%| Americas\n|-\n|valign=top|\n{{flb|SWE}} (1)<br />\n{{flb|SVK}} (9)<br />\n{{flb|RUS}} (11)<br />\n{{flb|BEL}} (24)<br />\n{{flb|FRA}} (25)<br />\n{{flb|ISL}} (\u2013)\n|valign=top|\n{{flb|FIN}} (2)<br />\n{{flb|EST}} (8)<br />\n{{flb|DEN}} (12)<br />\n{{flb|AUT}} (22)<br />\n{{flb|NED}} (28)\n|valign=top|\n{{flb|SUI}} (3)<br />\n{{flb|GER}} (7)<br />\n{{flb|POL}} (14)<br />\n{{flb|ESP}} (22)<br />\n{{flb|GBR}} (29)<br />\n{{flb|GEO}} (38)\n|valign=top|\n{{flb|CZE}} (4)<br />\n{{flb|NOR}} (6)<br />\n{{flb|SRB}} (20)<br />\n{{flb|ITA}} (21)<br />\n{{flb|SLO}} (27)<br />\n{{flb|LIE}} (30)\n|valign=top|\n{{flb|JPN}} (15)<br />\n{{flb|AUS}} (16)<br />\n{{flb|KOR}} (17)<br />\n{{flb|SIN}} (18)<br />\n{{flb|NZL}} (26)<br />\n{{flb|MYS}} (33)<br />\n{{flb|THA}} (\u2013)<br />\n|valign=top|\n{{flb|USA}} (10)<br />\n{{flb|CAN}} (13)<br />\n{{flb|JAM}} (32)\n|}\n\n==Europe==\nThe qualification rules are as follows:\n* The two best teams from each qualification group will qualify\n* The two best third placed teams will qualify\n** The calculation of the best 3rd teams will follow this order:\n*** 1. Average number of points \n*** 2. Average goal difference \n*** 3. Average scored goals\n*** 4. Drawing of lots\n\n===European Qualification 1===\n'''Dates:''' 3 \u2013 7 February 2016<ref name=\"European Qualification 1\">{{cite web\n | url = http://www.floorball.org/pages/EN/Mens-WFCQ-2016-EUR1-Slovakia\n | title = Men's World Championships 2016 Qualifications \u2013 European Qualification 1\n | date = 5 February 2016\n | website = www.floorball.org\n | publisher = [[International Floorball Federation]]\n | access-date = 6 February 2016}}</ref><br>\n'''Venue:''' [[Arena Klokocina]], [[Nitra]], [[Slovakia]]\n{{#invoke:sports table|main|style=WDL\n|res_col_header=Q\n|show_positions=n\n|winpoints=2\n\n|team1=SWE|name_SWE={{flb|SWE}}\n|team2=SVK|name_SVK={{flb|SVK}}\n|team3=RUS|name_RUS={{flb|RUS}}\n|team4=BEL|name_BEL={{flb|BEL}}\n|team5=ISL|name_ISL={{flb|ISL}}\n|team6=FRA|name_FRA={{flb|FRA}}\n|win_SWE=5|draw_SWE=0|loss_SWE=0|gf_SWE=106|ga_SWE=7\n|win_SVK=4|draw_SVK=0|loss_SVK=1|gf_SVK=50|ga_SVK=31\n|win_RUS=3|draw_RUS=0|loss_RUS=2|gf_RUS=43|ga_RUS=33\n|win_BEL=2|draw_BEL=0|loss_BEL=3|gf_BEL=23|ga_BEL=56\n|win_ISL=1|draw_ISL=0|loss_ISL=4|gf_ISL=19|ga_ISL=67\n|win_FRA=0|draw_FRA=0|loss_FRA=5|gf_FRA=13|ga_FRA=60\n\n|col_Q=green1|text_Q=Qualify for the 2016 Men's World Floorball Championships\n|result1=Q|result2=Q\n|col_Q3=lavender|text_Q3=Referred to the ranking of third-placed teams\n|result3=Q3\n|col_E=red1|text_E=Miss out on the 2016 Men's World Floorball Championships\n|result4=E|result5=E|result6=E\n|update=complete|source=\n}}\n\n{| style=\"width:70%;\" cellspacing=\"1\"\n|-\n!width=35%| !!width=15%|\n!\n|-\n| 3 February 2016\n|- style=font-size:90%\n|align=right|'''{{fl-rt|SWE}}'''||align=center|'''22''' \u2013 0||{{flb|BEL}}\n|- style=font-size:90%\n|align=right|{{fl-rt|ISL}}||align=center|